##China alone supplies 60% of the world's raw drugs, as us 'national security' suffers

I-CAIJING

By Barron's, China contributor

Editor | Kang Juan

Some of China's economic activity has stalled in the wake of the new crown pneumonia outbreak, as recent economic data have shown. The value of China's imports and exports fell 11 percent in the first two months of the year to us $591.99 billion, according to data released by the General Administration of Customs on March 7. Exports of US $292.45 billion, down 17.2 percent, imports of US $299.54 billion, down 4 percent, and trade deficit of US $7.09 billion, compared with a surplus of us $41.45 billion in the same period last year.

In March, the epidemic situation in China continued to gradually improve, the impact on economic activities has eased, and the scope for resuming production and work has continued to expand. But while the situation in China has improved, the number of infections outside the country has continued to rise. This situation has increased the imported risk of the epidemic in China, resulting in the movement of people is still limited to a certain extent, some pharmaceutical manufacturers can not resume full employment due to a shortage of workers. This has also created a "medical emergency" in the United States, which is heavily dependent on Chinese raw materials and medical supplies.

China's supply cut-off of bulk drug

The impact of the outbreak on the pharmaceutical supply chain has become a very worrying issue, the Barron's said in an article titled "How the outbreak affects the four key areas of the health care industry. " That is because some multinational pharmaceutical companies rely heavily on Chinese factories for their raw drugs, which could lead to supply problems at a time when the epidemic is still disrupting the Chinese economy.

Raw drug, the active ingredient API, whose procurement status is confidential, makes it difficult to know which drugs need ingredients from China, but it is certainly an important factor. Sanofi, the Chief Executive of Sny, which owns several bulk drug factories, told Barron's that 60% of the world's bulk drugs are made in China.

On the night of Feb. 27, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) reported the first drug shortage in the United States as a result of the outbreak, but did not say which drugs were affected. The shortage of drugs came much earlier than experts had expected, but the limited information provided by the FDA does not tell us how serious it is.

Pharmaceutical companies often have large stockpiles of Apis on hand, but those stockpiles can run out. Bernstein analyst Gaelic said Feb. 28 that there is only one case of a drug shortage that has not been taken seriously. But he cited industry executives who said a "spot shortage" of generic drugs in the US could occur in the second or early third quarter of this year.

Pharmaceutical companies have previously said they have not experienced a shortage of drugs. Merck & Co..Merckk, MRK, said in a statement, "the situation is constantly changing, but at this point, we do not expect the company's supply chain to be affected unless the supply disruptions caused by the outbreak continue in the coming months. "

Mylan, MYL CEO Heather Buresch said in a Feb. 27 earnings call that the outbreak could affect the company's supply chain. "given that our supply chain, operations and business are global, the company's performance could be affected, " she said.

"The longer this continues, the greater the risk for certain drugs, " said Mikell Guagno, director of practice and quality for Pharmacists at the American Society of Health-System Pharmacists

Now, all the pharmacist can do is wait. "everyone is preparing for what might happen, but no one knows how to deal with it now, " Guagno said.

India's decision on March 3 to restrict exports of some drugs and Apis came as the FDA reported a shortage of drugs in the United States, a further indication that the epidemic is disrupting the drug supply chain.

India is also a major producer of Apis, but it also needs to import raw materials from China to make medicines, the Barron's said in an article titled "Indian Authorities Restrict some drug exports. ". According to Reuters, the government says Indian manufacturers have only two to three months'supply of the material they need.

It's hard to say what that means for U.S. drug companies and consumers. Guagno said the supply chain was not transparent enough to judge the impact of India's decision on US consumers.

Donald Trump, talk about nationalization again

On March 2, the Donald Trump administration's working group on the new coronavirus outbreak met with representatives of pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies at the White House. Donald Trump told the meeting that the outbreak highlighted the importance of bringing back to the United States the manufacturing supply chain of previously outsourced drugs and equipment "urgently needed" to stop the spread of the virus. Donald Trump said the United States was already taking steps to reduce its dependence on access to key drugs and equipment through other countries.

"We want to produce certain drugs in the United States, " Donald Trump added. "Now these drugs are dependent not only on China, but also on a number of countries, including Ireland, and the United States is in great need of these drugs. "

At the end of February, the FDA said it learned that 20 drugs sold in the United States are manufactured in China, or rely on ingredients made only in China. In addition, as of 2018, China was the second largest exporter of drugs and biologics to the United States, and the largest exporter of medical equipment, according to the FDA.

U. S. officials have been warning about over-reliance on Chinese bulk drug makers. The U. s.-china Economic and Security Review Commission warned in November that reliance on Chinese drugs and Apis "poses risks to the U. S. economy and national Security. ".

Roth Gibson, senior adviser to the Hastings Center at the bioethics, said reliance on drugs from other countries made the United States vulnerable. "The outbreak is a wake-up call and this weakness in the US has been hit by supply chain disruptions. "

Americans, too, face a "CATCH-22"

After the recent rise in the number of infections in the United States, the United States has also begun to face a shortage of face masks in addition to medicines. Mikell Einhorn, president of Dealmed Medical Supplies, an American maker of masks and other products, reportedly said the company had received no new Supplies after the new pneumonia outbreak, the Chinese factories that normally make masks have not delivered them in two months.

China is the world's largest supplier of medical masks, industry experts say. Dealmed is not alone in facing supply shortages, although the Ministry of Commerce of the People's Republic of China says it will not restrict exports of medical masks.

Medicom, a Canadian maker of medical devices, has three factories in China, but its chief operating officer, Charles Ã‰douard Guillaume, says the Chinese government has requisitioned all its products, so none of them are exported.

"We estimate that about 80 percent of the world's masks are made in China, " Laverdur said. "overnight, the global supply of masks fell by 80 per cent and there is now very strong demand for existing capacity outside China. "

The United States has stockpiled about 30 million N95 masks, but could need as many as 300 million during an outbreak, health and Human Services Secretary Alex Azar told Congress on Feb. 25.

China is a major global manufacturer of face masks, and the annual export volume is stable at more than 70 percent of the production scale, said Li Xinggan, director general of the Ministry of Commerce of the People's Republic of China, at a regular online news conference held by the Ministry of Commerce on March 5. Masks are free-trade products, and the Chinese government does not impose any trade controls. Although China's mask production capacity has been rapidly increased, the supply and demand situation has improved greatly, but with a wide range of enterprises to resume production, mask demand is still at a high level, there is a large supply gap. In the previous phase of the epidemic prevention and control work, many countries have extended a helping hand to China. China is willing to overcome its own difficulties while providing assistance within its capacity to countries concerned in the field of medical protective materials such as face masks.
